# AI Hub - PySide6 text rules (no overflow, ever)

Every visible string in the app ultimately ends up in a `QLabel`. Qt
does not wrap labels by default, and even when you turn wrapping on the
parent layout still needs the right size policy or the second line just
clips. The screenshots that prompted this rule showed exactly that:
"Document summarised into 12 points" rendered, was wrapped, and then
the status icon on the right overlapped the wrapped second line because
the row was centered vertically.

These rules apply to every `.py` file under `src/` that creates Qt
widgets. They are mandatory.

## Hard rules - never break these

### 1. Build labels through the helpers in `src/qt/widgets.py`

Use `BodyLabel`, `MutedLabel`, `TitleLabel`, `SubtleLabel`,
`AccentLabel`, `custom_label`, or `IconLabel`. They all go through
`_make_label(...)` which calls `setWordWrap(True)` for you.

Direct `QLabel(text)` calls are **forbidden** because the default is
`wordWrap=False` and the text will clip. The only exception is
`ElidedLabel` (intentionally single-line, e.g. history file paths)
which sets the mode explicitly.

- Good: `BodyLabel("Document summary", theme=theme, size=13)`
- Good: `custom_label("Title", color=theme.text, size=14)`
- Bad: `QLabel("Document summary")` (no wrap, clips)

### 2. Never `setFixedWidth(...)` on a container that holds text

Fixed-width frames cut wrapped text in half because the content cannot
grow taller as it wraps. Use `setMaximumWidth(...)` instead so the
container can be narrower on small screens **and** grow when the text
is short.

The only two allowed `setFixedWidth` callers in the whole repo are the
left sidebar (`src/components/sidebar.py`, 280 px) and the right
context panel (`src/components/context_panel.py`, 336 px). Both have
internal scroll areas that absorb overflow. Everything else - chat
bubbles, warning pills, info cards, stat rows - uses `setMaximumWidth`.

- Good: `bubble.setMaximumWidth(420)` + word-wrapped `BodyLabel` inside
- Good: `pill.setMaximumWidth(320)`
- Bad: `bubble.setFixedWidth(380)` (text gets clipped at the second line)
- Bad: `pill.setFixedWidth(290)` (Czech translation gets cut)

### 3. The label "slot" frame must be Expanding / Preferred

Whenever a label is wrapped inside a `QFrame` that lives next to icons
in a `hbox` (the icon + title + status pattern), the slot frame must
have:

```python
slot.setSizePolicy(QSizePolicy.Policy.Expanding, QSizePolicy.Policy.Preferred)
row_layout.addWidget(slot, 1)
```

The `1` stretch in `addWidget(..., 1)` is mandatory, otherwise the slot
gets only its minimum size and the wrapped text overflows underneath
the next sibling widget.

### 4. AlignTop on rows where text can wrap

The common bug looks like this:

```python
# WRONG - status icon stays vertically centered even after the
# description wraps to two lines, so it visually overlaps line 2.
row_layout = hbox(...)
row_layout.setAlignment(Qt.AlignmentFlag.AlignVCenter)
row_layout.addWidget(badge)
row_layout.addWidget(info_slot, 1)
row_layout.addWidget(status_icon)
```

Whenever the middle slot contains a wrap-prone label and the row has
more than one widget on its right, set `AlignTop`:

```python
row_layout = hbox(...)
row_layout.setAlignment(Qt.AlignmentFlag.AlignTop)
```

The badge / icon will now hug the top of the row and the slot will
grow downward as the text wraps. This is the canonical fix for the
"Document summarised into 12 points" overflow.

`AlignVCenter` is only acceptable when the row is a strict single line
(navigation row with a short label, segmented buttons, etc.).

### 5. Chat bubbles use `setMaximumWidth`

Chat bubbles must shrink to their content but never grow beyond a
sensible limit:

```python
bubble = QFrame()
bubble.setMaximumWidth(420)  # right-side user, or left-side assistant
bubble.setSizePolicy(QSizePolicy.Policy.Maximum, QSizePolicy.Policy.Preferred)
```

`setFixedWidth` is forbidden on chat bubbles because the screenshots
show wrap issues on long single-line questions.

### 6. The `wrap_label_slot(widget)` helper

`src/qt/widgets.py` exposes a tiny helper:

```python
def wrap_label_slot(widget: QWidget) -> QWidget:
    """Mark a container as the expanding text slot in an icon+text+icon row."""
    widget.setSizePolicy(QSizePolicy.Policy.Expanding, QSizePolicy.Policy.Preferred)
    return widget
```

Use it on every "info" / "text_holder" / "title_holder" frame that
hosts wrap-prone labels. It keeps the policy uniform and lets `Grep`
audits find every slot at once.

## How to audit your work

Before opening a PR that touches any view-layer code, run these greps:

```
rg "setFixedWidth\(" src
rg "setAlignment\(Qt\.AlignmentFlag\.AlignVCenter\)" src
rg "QLabel\(" src --glob "!src/qt/widgets.py" --glob "!src/qt/markdown.py"
```

- The first should show only the two allowed callers (sidebar /
 context panel) and chip-like fixed-size widgets that hold no text
 (badges, dots, avatars, color swatches).
- The second should only flag single-line rows. If a hit owns a
 wrap-prone label, switch to `AlignTop`.
- The third should be empty (every `QLabel()` call should go through a
 helper).

## Don'ts

- Do **not** disable word wrap to "make a label fit in one line". If it
 needs to elide, use `ElidedLabel(..., mode=Qt.TextElideMode.ElideRight)`.
- Do **not** use `setMinimumWidth` to "reserve room" for text - the
 layout will not shrink on smaller windows. Use `setMaximumWidth` or
 leave it alone.
- Do **not** wrap a label in nested `QFrame` slots without giving the
 outer slot the Expanding policy. Stretch propagation stops at the
 first non-expanding parent.
- Do **not** add `setWordWrap(True)` after-the-fact on a raw `QLabel`
 to dodge rule 1 - go through the helper so future labels behave the
 same way.
